Medium: Find All Anagrams in a String (LeetCode 438)
The Concept: Find all start indices of p's anagrams in s.

The Shortcut: The window size is fixed to p.length(). Use an array or a Hash Map of size 26 to store character frequencies. Slide a fixed window across string s. If the frequency count array matches p's array exactly, you found an anagram.

1. Brute Force

For every substring of length p.length(), build a frequency map and compare it with p's frequency map.

Time Complexity
Building map for each window: O(k)
Total windows: O(n)
Total: O(n*k)

Code
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findAnagrams(String s, String p) {

        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        HashMap<Character, Integer> pMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (char ch : p.toCharArray()) {
            pMap.put(ch, pMap.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        int k = p.length();

        for (int i = 0; i <= s.length() - k; i++) {

            HashMap<Character, Integer> currMap = new HashMap<>();

            for (int j = i; j < i + k; j++) {
                char ch = s.charAt(j);
                currMap.put(ch, currMap.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
            }

            if (currMap.equals(pMap)) {
                ans.add(i);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}


2. Sliding Window using 2 HashMaps

Maintain:

pMap → frequency of pattern
windowMap → frequency of current window

Window size remains fixed at p.length().

Time Complexity
O(n) windows
HashMap.equals() can take O(26) for lowercase letters
Effectively O(n)

Code:
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findAnagrams(String s, String p) {

        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        HashMap<Character, Integer> pMap = new HashMap<>();
        HashMap<Character, Integer> windowMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (char ch : p.toCharArray()) {
            pMap.put(ch, pMap.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        int k = p.length();
        int i = 0;

        for (int j = 0; j < s.length(); j++) {

            char ch = s.charAt(j);
            windowMap.put(ch, windowMap.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);

            if (j - i + 1 > k) {

                char left = s.charAt(i);

                windowMap.put(left, windowMap.get(left) - 1);

                if (windowMap.get(left) == 0) {
                    windowMap.remove(left);
                }

                i++;
            }

            if (j - i + 1 == k) {
                if (windowMap.equals(pMap)) {
                    ans.add(i);
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}


3. Sliding Window using 1 HashMap (Most Interview-Friendly)

Store only the pattern frequencies.

When a character enters the window:

decrement its count

When a character leaves:

increment its count

Maintain a count variable representing how many distinct characters still need matching.

Time Complexity: O(n)

Code:
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findAnagrams(String s, String p) {

        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        HashMap<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();

        for (char ch : p.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        int count = map.size();

        int k = p.length();
        int i = 0;
        int j = 0;

        while (j < s.length()) {

            char ch = s.charAt(j);

            if (map.containsKey(ch)) {
                map.put(ch, map.get(ch) - 1);

                if (map.get(ch) == 0) {
                    count--;
                }
            }

            if (j - i + 1 < k) {
                j++;
            }
            else if (j - i + 1 == k) {

                if (count == 0) {
                    ans.add(i);
                }

                char left = s.charAt(i);

                if (map.containsKey(left)) {

                    if (map.get(left) == 0) {
                        count++;
                    }

                    map.put(left, map.get(left) + 1);
                }

                i++;
                j++;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}


| Approach              | Extra Space        | Time             |
| --------------------- | ------------------ | ---------------- |
| Brute Force           | `O(26)` per window | `O(n*k)`         |
| 2 HashMaps            | `O(26)`            | `O(n)`           |
| 1 HashMap + Count     | `O(26)`            | `O(n)`           |
| Frequency Arrays (26) | `O(26)`            | `O(n)` (fastest) |

Brute Force → 2 HashMaps → 1 HashMap + Count → Frequency Array (Optimal).

4. Frequency Array (Optimal)
Idea
pFreq[26] → frequency of characters in p
winFreq[26] → frequency of current window in s
Window size is fixed = p.length()
Compare both arrays whenever window size becomes k
Time Complexity
Building frequencies: O(k)
Sliding window: O(n)
Comparing arrays: O(26) ≈ constant

Overall:

O(n)
Space Complexity
O(26) = O(1)

Code:
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findAnagrams(String s, String p) {

        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        int[] pFreq = new int[26];
        int[] winFreq = new int[26];

        for (char ch : p.toCharArray()) {
            pFreq[ch - 'a']++;
        }

        int k = p.length();
        int i = 0;

        for (int j = 0; j < s.length(); j++) {

            winFreq[s.charAt(j) - 'a']++;

            if (j - i + 1 > k) {
                winFreq[s.charAt(i) - 'a']--;
                i++;
            }

            if (j - i + 1 == k) {

                if (Arrays.equals(pFreq, winFreq)) {
                    ans.add(i);
                }
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
