Even Better (Single Array + Match Count)

Instead of calling:

Arrays.equals(pFreq, winFreq)

for every window, maintain a count of matched characters.

This avoids comparing 26 elements repeatedly and is considered the most optimized implementation.

CODE:
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findAnagrams(String s, String p) {

        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();

        if (s.length() < p.length()) {
            return ans;
        }

        int[] freq = new int[26];

        for (char ch : p.toCharArray()) {
            freq[ch - 'a']++;
        }

        int i = 0;
        int count = p.length();

        for (int j = 0; j < s.length(); j++) {

            if (freq[s.charAt(j) - 'a'] > 0) {
                count--;
            }

            freq[s.charAt(j) - 'a']--;

            if (j - i + 1 > p.length()) {

                if (freq[s.charAt(i) - 'a'] >= 0) {
                    count++;
                }

                freq[s.charAt(i) - 'a']++;
                i++;
            }

            if (count == 0) {
                ans.add(i);
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}

